          "body": "The psalm closes with a single verse that moves from third-person theology to first-person doxology: 'All my springs of joy are in you' (87:7). The word *mayan* (spring, source of water) is the Old Testament's image for the source of life and vitality — Proverbs 5:15 uses it of a man's wife, Proverbs 25:26 uses it of a righteous man. To say 'all my springs of joy are in you' is to say that Zion is the source of everything that sustains, refreshes, and delights the worshipper — that nothing outside Zion can ultimately satisfy. Singers and flute players carry the declaration together (87:7), suggesting this is the congregation's united conclusion after the oracle has been heard. The pastoral force is direct: the theology of vv.1-6 — Zion founded, loved, established; nations enrolled as her citizens — must land as a personal doxology. The psalm does not end with doctrinal statement; it ends with the worshipper's life oriented toward the city where all joy originates. John Calvin noted that this is the psalm's practical burden: to wean the believer's affections from every competing source of joy and anchor them in the city of God."
