        "title": "Yahweh's radical preference — the election of Zion",
        "range": "87:1-2",
        "excerpt": "The LORD loves the gates of Zion more than all the other dwelling places of Jacob.",
        "body": "The psalm's opening verse is both historical and theological. 'His foundation is in the holy mountains' reaches back to Yahweh's choice of Jerusalem as the site of His dwelling — a choice formally enacted when David brought the ark to Zion (2 Samuel 6) and when Solomon built the temple (1 Kings 8). But the psalm does not merely rehearse history; it makes a theological claim about the nature of what Yahweh did: He *founded* Zion. The Hebrew *yesudah* uses the same root as Isaiah 28:16's 'cornerstone in Zion, a tested stone, a costly cornerstone for the foundation, firmly placed.' The city's security is entirely derivative of divine initiative.\n\nVerse 2 makes the claim more provocative: Yahweh loves Zion's gates **more than all the other dwelling places of Jacob**. This is electing, comparative love. Israel had multiple sacred sites — Shiloh had been the tabernacle's home for generations (1 Samuel 4); Bethel and Dan housed the northern kingdom's golden calves; Hebron was the city of the patriarchs' burial; Beersheba marked the southern boundary of the land. Yahweh is said to love Zion's gates more than all of them. This is the logic of election applied to geography: as Yahweh chose Israel over other nations (Deuteronomy 7:6), He chose Zion over other Israelite sites.\n\nThe 'gates' is a synecdoche for the entire city and its community — in the ancient Near East, the gate was the place of public assembly, judgment, commerce, and worship. To love the gates is to love the city at its most public, most communal, most active point. This is not a private, interior piety; it is civic, visible, embodied love for the place where the community gathers.\n\nFor the psalm's NT trajectory, this divine preference for Zion does not terminate on the earthly city but on the heavenly reality it prefigures. Hebrews 12:22 addresses believers as those who 'have come to Mount Zion and to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem' — the election of earthly Zion was always pointing beyond itself to the eschatological city.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yesudah* (founded, v.1) — from *yasad*, to lay a foundation; the noun form here is feminine, Zion being the implied subject even before she is named. *Ahav* (loves, v.2) — the covenant love verb used of Yahweh's love for Israel (Deuteronomy 7:8) and of His love for the righteous (Psalm 146:8); here applied to a city, the personification is deliberate. *Shaar* (gates) — the civic and judicial heart of the ancient city."
