        "excerpt": "Glorious things are spoken of you, O city of God. Selah.",
        "body": "Verse 3 is a pivot hinge between the election declaration of vv.1-2 and the oracle of enrollment in vv.4-6. 'Glorious things' (*nikbadot*, from *kavad*, 'to be heavy, weighty, glorious') are spoken of Zion. The passive construction — 'are spoken' — leaves the speaker ambiguous by design: in context, it is Yahweh who speaks these glorious things, as verse 4 will immediately demonstrate with the oracle beginning 'I shall mention.' The glorious things are not human praise of the city; they are divine declarations about it.\n\nThe address 'O city of God' (*ir ha-elohim*) is the psalm's only direct address to Zion, and it functions as a formal title. The same phrase appears in Psalm 46:4-5 ('There is a river whose streams make glad the city of God, the holy dwelling places of the Most High') — one of the Songs of Zion that Psalm 87 belongs to alongside Psalms 46, 48, and 76. These psalms share a common theological conviction: Jerusalem is uniquely Yahweh's city, and its security is His own.\n\nThe *Selah* after verse 3 is a liturgical instruction to pause — not merely a musical direction but a rhetorical device that says: hold this claim before the oracle unpacks it. The congregation in the temple courts would pause here, holding the weight of 'glorious things are spoken of you' before discovering what those glorious things are. The pause is itself interpretive: the glory of Zion is not self-evident from the city's appearance or power; it must be received by hearing the divine oracle that follows.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nikbadot* (glorious things, v.3) — plural of the *nif'al* participle of *kavad*; weighty, honorable, glorious things. The same root gives *kabod* (glory), Yahweh's manifest weightiness. *Selah* — of uncertain etymology; most likely a liturgical pause or a directive to lift the voice or instruments."
